{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UGMGaHYTZwhhe526s1Lif2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Host Workflow Design (`host.cloche`)\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-06\n     4→**Status:** Design\n     5→\n     6→## Problem\n     7→\n     8→The orchestrator's intake → process → output loop is hard-coded in Go\n     9→(`internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go`). Every project must follow the same flow:\n    10→pull task → generate prompt → dispatch `develop` container run. This can't be changed\n    11→without modifying Cloche itself. Projects that need different orchestration strategies\n    12→(push to GitHub for review, group tickets into feature branches, stacked commits, etc.)\n    13→have no extension point.\n    14→\n    15→## Solution: `host.cloche`\n    16→\n    17→A special workflow file at `.cloche/host.cloche`. It uses the same DSL as container\n    18→workflow files, with one additional step type (`workflow`). Steps in this file execute\n    19→on the **host machine**, not inside a container.\n    20→\n    21→The workflow named `main` in this file becomes the per-task orchestration loop\n    22→for that project. The Go daemon becomes the executor of this workflow rather than the\n    23→hard-coded logic holder.\n    24→\n    25→### File location\n    26→\n    27→```\n    28→.cloche/host.cloche\n    29→```\n    30→\n    31→If the file does not exist, the daemon falls back to the current hard-coded behavior\n    32→(pull task → LLM prompt generation → dispatch container workflow).\n    33→\n    34→---\n    35→\n    36→## DSL additions\n    37→\n    38→### New step type: `workflow`\n    39→\n    40→A step with `workflow_name` config key is a workflow-dispatch step. It dispatches a\n    41→named container workflow run and blocks until that run completes.\n    42→\n    43→```\n    44→step develop {\n    45→  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    46→  results = [success, fail]\n    47→}\n    48→```\n    49→\n    50→`workflow_name` is added to `knownStepConfigKeys` in `domain/workflow.go`.\n    51→\n    52→`StepTypeWorkflow` is added to the `StepType` enum in `domain/workflow.go`.\n    53→\n    54→The parser (`dsl/parser.go`) infers `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` is present\n    55→(same pattern as `run` → script, `prompt` → agent).\n    56→\n    57→### Prompt input for `workflow` steps\n    58→\n    59→The container workflow needs a prompt. By convention, a `workflow` step reads the\n    60→previous step's captured output file as the prompt. This is the primary data-passing\n    61→mechanism.\n    62→\n    63→An optional config key `prompt_step` overrides which step's output to read:\n    64→```\n    65→step develop {\n    66→  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    67→  prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    68→  results       = [success, fail]\n    69→}\n    70→```\n    71→\n    72→---\n    73→\n    74→## Step output capture\n    75→\n    76→Every step in a host workflow execution writes its output (stdout of `run` steps,\n    77→final response of `prompt` steps) to a file:\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→.cloche/<orch-run-id>/main/<step_name>.out\n    81→```\n    82→\n    83→`<orch-run-id>` is a unique ID for this orchestration invocation, formatted the same\n    84→way as workflow run IDs (e.g. `main-bold-hawk`).\n    85→\n    86→The daemon tracks the most recently completed step's output path and passes it to the\n    87→next step as `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT`.\n    88→\n    89→---\n    90→\n    91→## Environment variables injected into host steps\n    92→\n    93→All `run` and `prompt` steps receive:\n    94→\n    95→| Variable | Value |\n    96→|----------|-------|\n    97→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID being processed |\n    98→| `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE` | Task summary/title |\n    99→| `CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` | Task full body/description |\n   100→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory |\n   101→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output |\n   102→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the previous step's output file |\n   103→\n   104→For `workflow` steps, `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` is read automatically (unless `prompt_step`\n   105→overrides it).\n   106→\n   107→---\n   108→\n   109→## Executor: `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go`\n   110→\n   111→New file. Implements the host workflow execution loop.\n   112→\n   113→```go\n   114→type HostRunner struct {\n   115→    Dispatch  RunDispatcher      // existing: dispatches a container workflow run\n   116→    WaitRun   RunWaiter          // new: blocks until a run ID completes, returns final state\n   117→    AgentCmd  string             // command to invoke for prompt steps on host\n   118→}\n   119→\n   120→// RunWorkflow executes the named workflow from a parsed host.cloche Workflow\n   121→// for a single task. Returns the final result (\"done\" or \"abort\").\n   122→func (r *HostRunner) RunWorkflow(ctx context.Context, wf *domain.Workflow, task ports.Task, orchRunID string) (string, error)\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→Step execution:\n   126→\n   127→- **`script` step** (`run` key): `exec.Command` with env vars, stdout captured to\n   128→  `<step>.out`, stderr to `<step>.err`. Exit 0 → `success`, non-zero → `fail`.\n   129→- **`agent` step** (`prompt` key): invoke `AgentCmd` on host with the prompt file\n   130→  contents injected. Capture output. Exit 0 → `success`, non-zero → `fail`.\n   131→- **`workflow` step** (`workflow_name` key): read prompt from prev step's `.out` file\n   132→  (or `prompt_step` override), call `Dispatch`, then call `WaitRun` to block until\n   133→  the container run completes. Map `succeeded` → `success`, `failed`/`cancelled` →\n   134→  `fail`.\n   135→\n   136→`WaitRun` is a new port interface:\n   137→\n   138→```go\n   139→// RunWaiter blocks until the run with the given ID reaches a terminal state.\n   140→type RunWaiter interface {\n   141→    WaitRun(ctx context.Context, runID string) (domain.RunState, error)\n   142→}\n   143→```\n   144→\n   145→The gRPC server / store already has `GetRun`; the waiter can poll it with backoff or\n   146→subscribe to the `OnRunComplete` event. A simple polling implementation (1s interval)\n   147→is sufficient initially.\n   148→\n   149→---\n   150→\n   151→## Refactored `orchestrator.Orchestrator`\n   152→\n   153→`Orchestrator.Run()` is updated:\n   154→\n   155→**Current flow (hardcoded):**\n   156→1. Pull ready tasks\n   157→2. Claim task\n   158→3. Call `promptGen.Generate(task)`\n   159→4. Call `dispatch(workflow, projectDir, prompt)` → runID\n   160→5. (In-flight counter managed, `OnRunComplete` decrements it)\n   161→\n   162→**New flow (when `host.cloche` exists):**\n   163→1. Pull ready tasks\n   164→2. Claim task\n   165→3. Parse `.cloche/host.cloche` → find `main` workflow\n   166→4. Generate an `orchRunID` (`main-<namegen>`)\n   167→5. Spin up a goroutine: call `hostRunner.RunWorkflow(ctx, orch wf, task, orchRunID)`\n   168→6. On goroutine return: decrement in-flight, update task state (success/fail)\n   169→\n   170→The old `promptGen` and `dispatch` are still used as the **fallback** when\n   171→`host.cloche` is absent (no breaking change for existing projects).\n   172→\n   173→`WaitRun` needs access to the run store. Wire it in `initOrchestrator` in\n   174→`cmd/cloched/main.go`.\n   175→\n   176→---\n   177→\n   178→## Default `host.cloche` (from `cloche init`)\n   179→\n   180→```\n   181→# host.cloche — orchestration workflow (runs on host, not in container)\n   182→# Steps here execute as the daemon user. Keep operations simple and safe.\n   183→\n   184→workflow \"main\" {\n   185→  step prepare-prompt {\n   186→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   187→    results = [success, fail]\n   188→  }\n   189→\n   190→  step develop {\n   191→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   192→    results       = [success, fail]\n   193→  }\n   194→\n   195→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   196→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   197→  develop:success        -> done\n   198→  develop:fail           -> done\n   199→}\n   200→```\n   201→\n   202→And `.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` (created by init, chmod +x):\n   203→\n   204→```bash\n   205→#!/usr/bin/env bash\n   206→# Default prompt generator. Uses task env vars injected by cloched.\n   207→# Write the prompt to $CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT (also echoed to stdout).\n   208→set -euo pipefail\n   209→\n   210→prompt=\"## Task: ${CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE}\n   211→\n   212→${CLOCHE_TASK_BODY}\"\n   213→\n   214→echo \"$prompt\"\n   215→[ -n \"${CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT:-}\" ] && echo \"$prompt\" > \"$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT\"\n   216→```\n   217→\n   218→---\n   219→\n   220→## `.gitignore` update\n   221→\n   222→`cloche init` adds `.cloche/scripts/` is NOT gitignored (scripts are project config).\n   223→The orchestration run output dirs follow the same pattern as container run dirs:\n   224→`.cloche/main-*/` is gitignored via the existing `.cloche/*/` rule.\n   225→\n   226→---\n   227→\n   228→## Safety notes\n   229→\n   230→- Host steps run with the same OS privileges as the `cloched` process.\n   231→- No network isolation.\n   232→- `host.cloche` should only reference scripts that are committed to the project.\n   233→- Document that `prompt` steps in `host.cloche` invoke an LLM agent with full host\n   234→  filesystem access — use judiciously.\n   235→\n   236→---\n   237→\n   238→## Changes required\n   239→\n   240→| File | Change |\n   241→|------|--------|\n   242→| `internal/domain/workflow.go` | Add `StepTypeWorkflow`, add `workflow_name`/`prompt_step` to `knownStepConfigKeys` |\n   243→| `internal/dsl/parser.go` | Infer `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` key is present |\n   244→| `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go` | New: host workflow executor |\n   245→| `internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go` | Refactor `Run()` to use `HostRunner` when `host.cloche` exists; fall back to current behavior otherwise |\n   246→| `internal/ports/container.go` | Add `RunWaiter` interface |\n   247→| `cmd/cloched/main.go` | Wire `HostRunner` into orchestrator init |\n   248→| `cmd/cloche/init.go` | Create `host.cloche` and `scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` |\n   249→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Jkvrg5DQnwms7p32h2LiZt","session_id":"ba5bc30d-1b57-42d1-a8db-100c4b86f5e1","uuid":"78f8d1ce-27f4-4465-b37e-5fc5fad9fc60"}
